<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="delta-vs-distribution">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Sometimes the Dirac delta function introduced in Section 3.4 is called a <em>distribution</em>.
      Which terminology do you prefer, and why?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Mathematically, the Dirac delta cannot be treated as an ordinary function, because it does not
      have a pointwise value and its defining property
      <m>\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \delta(t)\,\varphi(t)\,dt = \varphi(0)</m>
      holds only when understood in the sense of linear functionals acting on test functions.
      Calling <m>\delta(t)</m> a <em>distribution</em> emphasizes this correct mathematical nature.
    </p>

    <p>
      On the other hand, in engineering, physics, and applied differential equations, the word
      <em>delta function</em> is often more intuitive: it suggests an “impulse concentrated at a single moment.”
      When solving ODEs via Laplace transforms, thinking of <m>\delta(t)</m> as an impulse is often the
      most natural way to interpret it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Your personal preference may depend on context:
      <ul>
        <li><strong>“Distribution”</strong> — when emphasizing rigor or explaining why
          <m>\delta(t)</m> is not an ordinary function.</li>
        <li><strong>“Delta function”</strong> — when working on applied problems, impulse response,
          or Laplace transforms, where the operational meaning is clear and useful.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-mcq-1">
  <title>Interpretation of the Dirac Delta</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      How is the Dirac delta <m>\delta(t)</m> interpreted?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>A concentrated unit impulse at <m>t=0</m> that inputs “1 unit of area” instantaneously.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Section 3.4 treats <m>\delta(t)</m> as an idealized impulse with total area 1.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A function equal to infinity for all <m>t</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—it is zero everywhere except at a single instant.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>An ordinary continuous function.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the delta is not a classical function; it is a distribution.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-mcq-2">
  <title>Laplace Transform of <m>\delta(t)</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the Laplace transform of <m>\delta(t)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}[\delta(t)](s) = 1</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  <m>{\cal L}[\delta(t)](s) = 1</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}[\delta(t)](s) = s</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the delta transform is constant, not growing with <m>s</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}[\delta(t)](s) = e^{-s}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that is the transform of <m>\delta(t-1)</m>, not <m>\delta(t)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-mcq-3">
  <title>Transform of a Shifted Delta</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the Laplace transform of the shifted delta <m>\delta(t-a)</m> for <m>a &gt; 0</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}[\delta(t-a)](s) = e^{-as}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The delta "picks out" the value at <m>t=a</m>, giving <m>e^{-as}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>{\cal L}[\delta(t-a)](s) = s e^{-as}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the factor <m>s</m> does not appear.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>{\cal L}[\delta(t-a)](s) = \delta(s-a)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the Laplace transform is not another delta distribution.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-mcq-4">
  <title>Meaning of Impulse Response</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What does the <em>impulse response</em> of a linear ODE represent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The solution of the ODE when the input is a delta impulse <m>\delta(t)</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The impulse response is the solution when the forcing is <m>\delta(t)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The solution for an arbitrary forcing <m>f(t)</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that is the general forced solution, not specifically the impulse response.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The steady-state response only.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the impulse response includes transient behavior as well.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-mcq-5">
  <title>Simple Impulse‑Driven ODE</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the IVP  
      <m>x'' + x = \delta(t)</m>, <m>x(0)=0</m>, <m>x'(0)=0</m>.  
      What is <m>X(s)</m>, the Laplace transform of the solution?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>X(s) = \dfrac{1}{s^{2}+1}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Laplace transforming gives  
          <m>s^{2}X(s) + X(s) = 1</m>, hence <m>X(s)=1/(s^{2}+1)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>X(s) = \dfrac{s}{s^{2}+1}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that corresponds to initial velocity, not a delta input.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>X(s)=1</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the transform must include the system’s denominator <m>s^{2}+1</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-open-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the Laplace transform of <m>\delta(t-3)</m>.  
      Then, compute the Laplace transform of <m>5\,\delta(t-3)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
We have
    <me>
      {\cal L}[\delta(t-a)](s) = e^{-as}.   
    </me>
    <p>
      Therefore:
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}[\delta(t-3)](s) = e^{-3s}.   
    </me>

    <p>
      Linearity of the Laplace transform gives:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> {\cal L}[5\,\delta(t-3)](s)
        \amp = 5\,{\cal L}[\delta(t-3)] </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = 5 e^{-3s}.    </mrow>
    </md>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="delta-open-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP
    </p>
    <me>
      x' + 2x = \delta(t), \qquad x(0)=0.
    </me>
    <p>
      (This solution is the impulse response of the system.)
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Take Laplace transforms.</strong></p>

    <p>
      The Laplace transform of <m>x'</m> is <m>sX(s) - x(0) = sX(s)</m>.  
      Also, <m>{\cal L}[\delta(t)](s) = 1</m>.   
    </p>

    <me>
      sX(s) + 2X(s) = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for <m>X(s)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s) = \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>2. Invert the transform.</strong></p>

    <p>
      The inverse Laplace transform of <m>1/(s+2)</m> is <m>x(t)=e^{-2t}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      This satisfies the jump condition created by the delta impulse at <m>t=0</m>,
      and it obeys the initial condition <m>x(0)=0</m> in the appropriate distributional sense.
    </p>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="impulse-response-delta">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP (find the impulse response)
    </p>

    <me>
      x'' + x' + x = \delta(t), 
      \qquad
      x(0)=0,\; x'(0)=0.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Take the Laplace transform of the ODE.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Using the formulas  
      <m>{\cal L}\{x''\} = s^{2}X(s) - sx(0) - x'(0)</m> and  
      <m>{\cal L}\{x'\} = sX(s) - x(0)</m>,  
      and given <m>x(0)=0</m>, <m>x'(0)=0</m>, we obtain:
    </p>

    <me>
      s^{2}X(s) + sX(s) + X(s) = {\cal L}\{\delta(t)\} = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Factor the left-hand side:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s^{2} + s + 1)X(s) = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Hence
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s) = \frac{1}{s^{2} + s + 1}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>2. Complete the square.</strong></p>

    <me>
      s^{2} + s + 1
      =
      \left(s + \tfrac{1}{2}\right)^{2}
      + \tfrac{3}{4}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s)
      = 
      \frac{1}{\left(s + \tfrac12\right)^{2} + \left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^{2}}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>3. Use the standard inverse Laplace transform</strong></p>

    <p>
      The formula
      <m>{\cal L}^{-1}\!\left\{
         \dfrac{1}{(s+a)^{2} + b^{2}}
       \right\}
       =
       e^{-at}\,\dfrac{1}{b}\sin(bt)</m>
      applies with
      <m>a = \tfrac12</m> and <m>b = \tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>.
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> x(t)
      \amp =
      e^{-t/2}
      \cdot
      \frac{1}{\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}
      \sin\!\left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}t\right) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\,e^{-t/2}
      \sin\!\left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}t\right). </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      This satisfies the ODE in the distributional sense and obeys 
      the initial conditions exactly.
    </p>

  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives34">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
 Use limits of shrinking rectangular pulses to justify the formal properties of <m>\delta (t)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Apply the Laplace transform of the Dirac delta to solve differential equations with impulsive forcing.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Interpret impulse responses to understand how a system reacts to instantaneous inputs and generalize this to more complex inputs.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


